<div class="indented"><a id="comment-175"></a>

    

<div id="post-175" class="forum-post clear-block posted-by-1 post-by-starter">
  <div class="forum-post-info clear-block">
    <div class="forum-posted-on">
      November 30, 2011 - 2:43pm
          </div>

          <span class="forum-in-reply-to"><a href="cost-living-vietnam-its-really-cheap.html#comment-170" class="active">(Reply to #63)</a></span>
    
        
    <span class="forum-post-number"><a href="cost-living-vietnam-its-really-cheap2679.html?page=1#comment-175" class="active">#109</a></span>
  </div> 
  <div class="forum-post-wrapper">
    <div class="forum-post-panel-sub">
              <div class="author-pane">tomo
</div>          </div>

    <div class="forum-post-panel-main clear-block">
      
      <div class="forum-post-content">
        <p>In Vietnam $2500 is a rather large sum of money considering it's 25 times as much as many people make per month.  ADSL is available throughout the country so don't worry about that.  You may also want to get 3G for your phone or as a USB dongle.  Apartments are far less common than houses.  If you only plan to stay in Vietnam a short while, then you will probably go for a furnished house or serviced apartment.  Living in an apartment means you will most likely not get to know your neighbors, and your neighbors will likely be other foreigners.</p>
<p>The main city in the south would be Saigon, of course.  By far it is the biggest city with the most going on.  If you would like to live on the beach, then either Nha Trang or Mui Ne.  If you would like a cooler climate in the highlands, then Da Lat.</p>
<p>For 6 months, you can get a 3 month tourist visa and renew it once.  You can renew without leaving the country and any travel agent can arrange it for you.</p>
      </div>

      
          </div>
  </div> 
  <div class="forum-post-footer clear-block">
